items.title: Copying of context into _var prevents the use of more complex browser context objects
items.body:
Basically, I'm trying to stub out enough of a browser DOM and associated functionality to run some JS from the web.

I implemented most of this as a complex class that looks like a dict to pass through as the context object to `EvalJs()`, but it turns out that doesn't work since it seems `EvalJs()` copies everything in the passed context into it's internal `_var` member. 

Is there a reason for this copy? It'd be nice if instead the lookup operations just kept the context parameter around, and used it directly when objects aren't overridden.

I can put together a PR for this if it's something you're open to.

items.title: Bug in comma operator
items.body:
The following statement gives the expected output in Node.js:
```
> var a = {}; (a.a=1), (a.b={a: a.a}); console.log(a);
{ a: 1, b: { a: 1 } }
```
But in js2py, it gives different output:
```
>>> js2py.eval_js('var a = {}; (a.a=1), (a.b={a: a.a}); console.log(a);')
{'a': 1, 'b': {'a': None}}
```
It looks as if the first sub-expression of the comma operator, `(a.a=1)`, has not taken effect when the second, `(a.b={a: a.a})`, is evaluated. The problem does not occur if you replace the comma with a semicolon.

I have been unable to reproduce this issue with simpler assignments, like `(a.a=1), (a.b=a.a)`, so I'm not totally sure I understand the bug, but I think it's pretty clear that there is a bug.

I discovered this when using Babel 7 to compile some ES2016+ code into ES5 and translating that with `js2py.translate_file()` (which made tracking down the problem pretty difficult). Babel apparently sometimes uses the comma operator in places where it wasn't used in the input code.

items.title: += and -= treated as =
items.body:
When python is added to the js context, js2py seems to ignore `+=` and` -=` and treats this as `=`. See example below.

```
import js2py

class Foo:
    def __init__(self, bar):
        self.bar = bar

context = js2py.EvalJs({'foo': Foo(5)})

context.execute('foo.bar = 10')
print(context.foo.bar)  # prints 10

context.execute('foo.bar += 15')
print(context.foo.bar)  # prints 15 expected 25

context.execute('foo.bar -= 2')
print(context.foo.bar)  # prints 2 expected 23
```

Is this a known issue? And is there a way to circumvent this?

items.title: [VM] Subtracting from object properties
items.body:
Found a tricky one :)

This one works fine:

```py
eval('''var v=44; v-=12; throw v;''')  # throws 36
```

And this one does not:

```py
eval('''var o={p: 44}; o.p-=12; throw o.p;''')  # throws -36
```

After quite some head scratching I managed to find that the arguments are reversed in [sub_op function](https://github.com/PiotrDabkowski/Js2Py/blob/b1bbbeb0bcfef6f9548217f51caa4545545de550/js2py/internals/operations.py#L113) in the 2nd case. That has brought me to [STORE_MEMBER_OP](https://github.com/PiotrDabkowski/Js2Py/blob/b1bbbeb0bcfef6f9548217f51caa4545545de550/js2py/internals/opcodes.py#L421) where `value` and `get_member(left, name, ctx.space)` might need swapping (and perhaps once more three lines just above), but I'm totally guessing on this one.

If that's correct, I can provide a pull request with a fix if you like.

items.title: [VM] 'With' and 'jump outside' don't play well together
items.body:
I know 'with' is not supported in the old translator, but it seems to be implemented in the VM (that's also one of the reasons I'm trying it out), and it also seems to work most of the time so far, but I encountered an issue that I can't figure out, unfortunately:

This code runs well:

```js
        var foo = {bar: function() {}};
        with(foo) {
          bar();
        }
```

But this one does not and it throws _JsException: TypeError: undefined or null can't be converted to object_:

```js
        var foo = {bar: function() {}};
        with(foo) {
          if (true) {
            bar();
          }
        }
```

I've only been able to figure out that in the 1st case the `eval` function of `WITH` is called once, and in the 2nd one it is called twice with `undefined` at the top of the stack in the 2nd call.

By uncommenting a line I've found in `_execute_fragment_under_context` function that prints the opcodes, I can see a difference in execution:

For the code that runs well:

```
14 LOAD_UNDEFINED()
15 POP()
16 LOAD(u'bar',)
17 CALL_NO_ARGS()
2 LOAD_UNDEFINED()
3 JUMP(2,)
7 JUMP(3,)
4 POP()
5 LOAD_UNDEFINED()
6 RETURN()
18 NOP()
0   <-- this is printed by `print typ` in WITH.eval
```

And the other one:

```
14 LOAD_UNDEFINED()
15 LOAD_BOOLEAN(True,)
16 JUMP_IF_FALSE(7,)
17 POP()
18 LOAD(u'bar',)
19 CALL_NO_ARGS()
2 LOAD_UNDEFINED()
3 JUMP(2,)
7 JUMP(3,)
4 POP()
5 LOAD_UNDEFINED()
6 RETURN()
20 JUMP(8,)
2   <-- this is printed by `print typ` in WITH.eval
```

I think the jump shouldn't be 'outside' in this case, but that's pretty much all sense I could make out of it.

items.title: [VM] jsstring.substring, slice indices must be integers
items.body:
Running the following code will raise a _TypeError: slice indices must be integers or None or have an __index__ method_

```py
seval.eval_js_vm("'hello world'.substring(5);")
```

Actually I think this one is pretty easy. Apparently, the [substring function](https://github.com/PiotrDabkowski/Js2Py/blob/bb75a7eca54eac3ecde8183c0985ae8b15a10a95/js2py/internals/prototypes/jsstring.py#L262) arguments are of a float type for some reason, and the `start` variable in should be cast to integer, similarly to `end` variable just below:

```py
start = to_int(get_arg(args, 0))
```

function sign(roomId, time, did) {
    FlashEmu.BUILTIN = 'builtin.abc';
    FlashEmu.PLAYERGLOBAL = 'playerglobal.abc';
    FlashEmu.setGlobalFlags({
        enableDebug: false,
        enableLog: false,
        enableWarn: false,
        enableError: false
    });
    const emu = new FlashEmu({
        readFile(filename) {
            return fetch(filename)
                .then(res => res.arrayBuffer())
                .then(buf => new Uint8Array(buf).buffer);
        }
    });
    emu.runSWF('douyu.swf', false).then(() => {
        const CModule = emu.getProperty('sample.mp', 'CModule');
        const xx = emu.getPublicClass('mp');
        CModule.callProperty('startAsync');
        console.log('sign', roomId, time, did);
        let StreamSignDataPtr = CModule.callProperty('malloc', 4);
        let outptr1 = CModule.callProperty('malloc', 4);
        let datalen = xx.callProperty('sub_2', parseInt(roomId), parseInt(time), did.toString(), outptr1, StreamSignDataPtr);
        let pSign = CModule.callProperty('read32', StreamSignDataPtr);
        let sign = CModule.callProperty('readString', pSign, datalen);
        let pOut = CModule.callProperty('read32', outptr1);
        let out = CModule.callProperty('readString', pOut, 4);
        CModule.callProperty('free', StreamSignDataPtr);
        CModule.callProperty('free', outptr1);
        console.log('sign result', sign, out);
        let obj = new Object();
        obj.sign = sign;
        obj.cptl = out;
        let string = JSON.stringify(obj);
        document.write(string);
    }).catch(e => console.error(e));
};

items.title: Tuples from pyimport functions get converted to lists
items.body:
In my `p.py` i have the following:

```
def tuple():
    return( ( 1, 2 ) )
def list():
    return( [ 1, 2 ] )
def compare( v1, v2 ):
    print str( v1.__dict__ ) == str( v2.__dict__ )
    print str( v1._obj.__dict__ ) == str( v2._obj.__dict__ )
```

And when I run this, I see no differences:

```
python -c 'import js2py; js2py.eval_js("pyimport p; p.compare( p.tuple(), p.list() );")'
True
True
True
```

For some reason the third True get's printed when I do `pyimport p;`, but this is irrelevant for this issue.

items.title: Is there any way to limit scope?
items.body:
Right now, as I understand, eval_js resulting code does not have any access to locals, globals or to other variables.

Is there any way to pass some dictionary with variables that evaluated will have access to?

E.g. like stdlib does it - they allow you to pass any dictionary to the scope of evaluated code.

items.title: js2py.base.PyJsException: ReferenceError: print is not defined
items.body:
Playing with translation, I'm looking at how js2py plays with JS generated by emscripten from C++ files (I know there are other ways to do C++ to Python). But I keep getting `js2py.base.PyJsException: ReferenceError: print is not defined`. 

I've looked at [zopfli.js](https://github.com/imaya/zopfli.js) which is pretty straightforward. 

I've converted [zopfli.min.js](https://github.com/imaya/zopfli.js/blob/master/bin/zopfli.min.js) with js2py, see [zopfli.zip](https://github.com/PiotrDabkowski/Js2Py/files/694568/zopfli.zip)

items.title: Recursion depth error on large Js files using translated esprima.js
items.body:
SOLUTION:

Change python's recursion limit to ~4k.

---

Found a potential issue while parsing large files such as angular.js (1.5.8).

```
file = open("angular.js")
input = file.read()
file.close()

#import esprima
ast = esprima.parse(input)
```

This produces a `RecursionError: maximum recursion depth exceeded` error with a stack trace showing calls to the following:

```
return Js(self.code(*args))
var.put('result', var.get('parser')())
return self.call(self.GlobalObject, args)
arguments = PyJsArguments(args, self) # tuple will be converted to arguments object.
RecursionError: maximum recursion depth exceeded
```

In python 3 the following error is also thrown:

```
During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred:
.
.
.
return Js(self.code(*args))
var.put('expr', var.get('inheritCoverGrammar')((var.get('parseNewExpression') if var.get('matchKeyword')(Js('new')) else var.get('parsePrimaryExpression'))))
return self.call(self.GlobalObject, args)
raise MakeError('RangeError', e.message if not isinstance(e, NotImplementedError) else 'Not  implemented!')
AttributeError: 'RecursionError' object has no attribute 'message'
```

The `parse_js()` function can parse the input without error.

items.title: Disable pyimport by default, for security
items.body:
I'm exploring the use of this library for a project I'm working on, and it looks amazing. I am interested in using this library to parse and execute functions from potentially untrusted JavaScript files, so I am concerned by the availability of the `pyimport` keyword. Is it possible to add an option to enable/disable this feature, _and_ have it disabled by default?

Doing this would make the default behaviour of Js2Py much safer and similar to standard JavaScript.

items.title: Support generic use of Array.prototype.forEach?
items.body:
Here is the test case:

import js2py
t = r'''[].forEach.call("test", function(ch) { console.log(ch) });'''

Information from the spec:

NOTE The forEach function is intentionally generic; it does not require that its this value be an Array object. Therefore it can be transferred to other kinds of objects for use as a method. Whether the forEach function can be applied successfully to a host object is implementation-dependent.

I'm asking about this because I'm working on the unimplemented functions in prototypes/jsarray.py and this issue is making some of my (pre-submission) tests fail.

items.title: Forward slash handling broken
items.body:
Here is the test case:

import js2py
t = r'''function test() {return "test failed!".replace(new RegExp('\\sfailed','g'), ' passed')}'''
print js2py.eval_js(t)()

Running it returns "test failed!", but if you change the pattern to '\\\\sfailed' it will return "test passed!". I recorded what passed through PyJsString.**init**() and it spit out:

test failed!
\sfailed
g
sfailed
 passed
test failed!

It it unescapes once (which I think is the correct behavior), but does it again later for some reason. Sorry I don't have any more information, I just found this program last night and don't know enough to effectively track down bugs yet.

items.title: Feature suggestion
items.body:
This is a secondary issue.  If there's a file ending in

,"created_at":"2015-07-11 22:45:53"},{

Your fixer will cure the problem and place any {}[] characters as needed for completion.

However, if in the above example the file ends in

,"creat

The closing quote will be placed, however the value part of the  **key : value** pair will be missing, and prevent json from parsing.

My temporary suggested fix is to iterate through your fixer, removing the last character until I get the fixed json to validate; but perhaps there's a better method.

Having a license file say the code is under MIT, but `setup.py` indicate that it is under GPL creates  confusion.

I've changed `setup.py` from GPL to MIT in the linked pull request, since you have only recently added the explicit license.txt file where as the GPL keyword in `setup.py` was in the first commit of that file, and choosing to add an entire license file seems like a clear decision on which license you actually wanted to use for the project.
